Consider a system of two particles with spin $1/2$. The system is described by a composite wave function
\begin{equation}
|Psi\rangle = |Phi\rangle_1 \otimes |Phi\rangle_2. 
\end{equation}
We know that $ |\Phi\rangle_1 $ is an eigenstate of the x component of the spin of particle 1 (the $\hat{S}_{1x}$ operator) with an eigenvalue $\hbar/2$ and that |\Phi\rangle_2 $ is the eigenstate of the y component of the spin of particle 2 (the operator $\hat{S}_{2y}$) with eigenvalue $-\hbar/2$. What is the probability that a measurement of total spin squared, $\mathbf{\hat{S}}^2=(\hat{\mathbf{S}}_{(1)}+\hat{\mathbf{S}}_{(2)})^2$, performed on the $|\Psi \rangle$ state yields $\hbar^2 $?

A particle of mass $m$ is subjected to a harmonic potential 
\begin{equation}
\hat{V}= \frac{1}{2}m\omega^2 \hat{x^2}
\end{equation}
and, at time $t=0$ it is in a $|\psi(t=0)\rangle$ state determined by the following conditions:
\begin{enumerate}
\item each energy measurement gives certain values $E$ which satisfy the relation $ \hbar \omega < E < 3\hbar \omega $
\item the mean value of the energy is $ \langle E \rangle = \frac{11}{6} \hbar \omega $
\item the mean value of the position is $ \langle x \rangle = -\sqrt{\frac{8\hbar}{9m\omega}} $
\end{enumerate}
Write the quantum state $|\psi(t=0)\rangle$ explicitly in terms of the eigenstates of the harmonic oscillator, $|phi_n\rangle$.
[Tip: in what follows, it may be useful to express the position operator in terms of the creation and destruction operators $\hat{a}$ and $\hat{a^{\dagger}}$].
